'''Mioya Shrine''' (みおやじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Tenjinbara, Minatomachi, {{ill|lt=Okinoshima Town|Q1205039|qid=Q1205039|1=Okinoshima, Shimane}}, {{ill|lt=Oki District|Q735735|qid=Q735735|1=Oki District, Shimane}}, {{ill|lt=Shimane Prefecture|Q132751|qid=Q132751|1=Shimane Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and under the {{ill|lt=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was classified as a {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The shrine enshrines the following two deities<ref name="Explanation plaque">Explanation plaque on the shrine grounds.</ref>.
; Principal deity
:* {{ill|lt=Mizuhanome|Q8191796|qid=Q8191796|lt=Mizuhanome-no-Kami|1=Mizuhanome}}
; Associated deity
:* {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}

This shrine is identified with the “Mioya Shrine” listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Register of Deities|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, but this identification dates only from after the late Edo-period work *Oki Kokishū*. Medieval and early modern sources instead describe it as a shrine dedicated to {{ill|lt=Tenjin faith|Q66890725|qid=Q66890725|lt=Tenman Tenjin|1=Tenjin faith}} {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}. This is understood to be because, at some point, Tenman Tenjin was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kanjō|1=UNKNOWN}} at Mioya Shrine, and as devotion to Tenman Tenjin increased, it became better known than the original Mioya Shrine deity {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}. The associated deity Sugawara no Michizane corresponds to this Tenman Tenjin, and even today Mioya Shrine itself is commonly called “Tenjin-san” {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}.

There is another shrine of the same name, Mioya Shrine, in Hatta Enokihara, Okinoshima Town; according to tradition, the deity of that shrine is said to have drifted to become the Mioya Shrine at Tenjinbara<ref>“Gokokuji Village,” *Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei 33: Place Names of Shimane Prefecture*. Heibonsha, 1995.</ref>.

=== History ===
=== Overview ===
The date of foundation is unknown {{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}. The hill behind the shrine buildings is also said to be an {{ill|lt=ancient burial mound|Q1141225|qid=Q1141225|1=Kofun}}<ref name="Explanation plaque"/>{{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1983}}.

In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Register of Deities|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō (era)|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|lt=Enchō|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}), “Mioya Shrine” is listed in {{ill|lt=Oki Province|Q1063829|qid=Q1063829|1=Oki Province}} {{ill|lt=Shūki District|Q10920245|qid=Q10920245|1=Suki district}}, and this shrine is identified with that entry {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}. The *Oki Jinmyōchō* also records “Junior Fourth Rank, Mioya Myōjin,” but details of changes during the medieval period are unknown {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}.

A ridge tag from {{ill|lt=Tenmon (era)|Q1192853|qid=Q1192853|lt=Tenmon|1=Tenbun}} 22 ({{ill|lt=1554|Q6570|qid=Q6570|1=1554}}) refers to “Tenman Daijizai Tenjin,” and ridge tags from {{ill|lt=Shōhō|Q1146192|qid=Q1146192|1=Shōhō}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1646|Q6930|qid=Q6930|1=1646}}) and {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 10 ({{ill|lt=1670|Q7606|qid=Q7606|1=1670}}) also describe it as a shrine dedicated to Tenman Tenjin {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}. In addition, the *Inshū Shichō Gōki* from {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 7 ({{ill|lt=1667|Q7588|qid=Q7588|1=1667}}) and the *Inshūki* from {{ill|lt=Jōkyō|Q1146221|qid=Q1146221|1=Jōkyō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1688|Q7671|qid=Q7671|1=1688}}) both record it as a Tenmangū {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}. Later, beginning with the late Edo-period *Oki Kokishū*, which records the name “Gōso Shrine,” various works thereafter note that it should be identified with the “Mioya Shrine” of the *Engishiki* register {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Kami)|2000}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|qid=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, the shrine name was fixed as “Mioya Shrine,” and in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}) it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} under the {{ill|lt=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} {{Sfn|Mioya Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1983}}.

=== Divine rank ===
* Junior Fourth Rank (*Oki Jinmyōchō*) — recorded as “Mioya Myōjin.”

